prompt_template:
Create a {ASPECT_RATIO} image in the "Manga Dossier Blueprint Poster" visual style.

Subject: {SUBJECT}
Action: {SUBJECT_ACTION}
Prop/Product: {PRODUCT_OR_PROP}
Location: {LOCATION}
Background: {BACKGROUND_ELEMENTS}
Main text: {MAIN_TEXT}
Secondary text: {SECONDARY_TEXT}
Accent symbol: {ACCENT_SYMBOL}
Wardrobe/styling: {WARDROBE_STYLE}
Style fidelity anchors: {STYLE_FIDELITY_ANCHORS}
Source content to avoid: {SOURCE_CONTENT_TO_AVOID}

Apply these style rules: Make the image a distressed manga editorial dossier poster on warm off-white speckled paper. Build a layered layout with one oversized grayscale ink portrait, one smaller dynamic foreground figure or product vignette, a deep cobalt blueprint rectangle behind the subject, inset monochrome panels, compact metadata blocks, narrow side annotation rails, registration ticks, and a boxed catalog number. Use oversized condensed all-caps sans-serif headline typography with weathered black and cobalt ink, tight stacked hierarchy, tiny uppercase labels, and small profile-copy blocks. Render the subject with crisp manga linework, crosshatching, cel-shaded grayscale planes, textured halftone, and angular silhouette language. Add bright cyan hand-painted energy, smoke, wind, splash, or ribbon strokes that sweep across the foreground and connect the panels. Keep the palette limited to cream paper, charcoal black, cool gray, deep cobalt, navy shadow, and cyan accent. Preserve flat print lighting, screenprint distress, scuffed ink, worn paper, rough blue-panel edges, and controlled editorial density. For 9:16, favor a tall collectible poster with the title column and metadata along the side; for 16:9, expand the same dossier system into a wide editorial spread while preserving the portrait-title-action hierarchy.

Avoid: no photorealism, no 3D render, no glossy vector art, no smooth gradients, no cinematic bokeh, no full realistic background scene, no platform watermark, no QR code, no creator signature, no franchise logo, no pirate motif, no phoenix motif, no skull-and-crossbones mark, no copied source names, no copied source quote, no source character likeness.

Important content rule: match the reference style first, then change the source content. Use new subjects, new scene details, new props or products, and new text, while preserving the style fidelity anchors.
